ce:section.ce:para:
A CDs-enhanced synergistic removal mechanism of adsorption and photocatalysis for CNH was proposed (Fig. 10
                        ). First, Cr(VI) ions were absorbed on the CNH surface due to the strong electrostatic attraction between the protonated amino group of CDs and Cr(VI) ions. Under UV light irradiation, α-FeOOH was excited to generate photogenerated electrons and holes. Moreover, the loading of CDs could enhance the separation and transfer of the photogenerated electrons from the α-FeOOH to the CDs. Some photogenerated electrons were captured by Cr(VI) ions, which were reduced to Cr(III) ions via electronic reduction. Some photogenerated electrons were bound to O2 for generating O2
                        −, which could further reduce Cr(VI) ions to Cr(III) ions. The Cr(III) ions leave the surface of CDs because of the electrostatic repulsion between amino-modified CDs and Cr(III) ions. The abovementioned CDs-enhanced synergistic mechanism is helpful for the design and synthesis of efficient bifunctional materials for removing heavy metals.
